<h2>Exceptionally dry and sunny April over much of Europe</h2>
<br><br>
April 2020 was very warm and exceptionally sunny and dry in much of Europe as a result of high pressure systems dominating for almost the entire month. As shown in Figure 1, large parts of central and western Europe, from the Netherlands and northern France in the west to Kazakhstan in the east, experienced in April 250 to 300 sunshine hours, locally even above 300 hours. For large parts of this area these monthly totals correspond to a surplus of 100 to 150 hours or more than 150% of normal. In order to show how unusual these sunshine duration totals were, the monthly totals were put into the context of the 1986-2015 reference period by classifying them into categories from "exceptionally below" through "average" to "exceptionally above" average sunshine duration.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/apr2020/C3Surf_SoC_April_fig1.png"><img alt="" src="../images/apr2020/C3Surf_SoC_April_fig1.png" width="500px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Left: Monthly sunshine duration totals for April 2020. Right: Areas with exceptional amounts of sunshine duration totals for April 2020. The qualifications "exceptionally above (below) average", "above (below) average", and "average" relate to the percentile ranges >90 (<10), 67-90 (10-33) and 33-67 as calculated from the climatological period 1986-2015. (Source: http://www.dwd.de/rcc-cm)</em>
<br><br>
As shown in Figure 1 on the right, for most of western, central and eastern Europe, monthly sunshine totals for April were "exceptionally above" average (as indicated by the dark red color), only for the Iberian Peninsula the sunshine duration totals were "below average" or even "exceptionally below average". Several European countries reported new sunshine duration records: It was the sunniest April on record for the UK, the Netherlands and Germany and the second sunniest April for Austria.
These exceptionally sunny conditions in April 2020 are also reflected in the monthly cloud coverage which was exceptionally low with cloud coverages lower than 40% over much of western, central and eastern Europe as shown in Figure 15.
<br><br>
Fewer clouds also meant less rain and hence, for many countries, April was not only exceptionally sunny but also exceptionally dry. For many of the affected countries, the dryness started already around 20 March and continued during almost the whole month of April. In Germany, for example, less than 10 mm of rain had fallen across the country between 14 March and 18 April. Switzerland and France, too, reported very little precipitation during more than 40 days in this period. As a result of this extended dry spell April closed with a large precipitation deficit of 30 to 50 mm for several countries in western, central and also eastern Europe. This deficit corresponds to much below or even exceptionally below average precipitation as shown in Figure 2 on the right.
<br><br>
