<br><br>
In western, central and eastern Europe the number of warm days was much larger than normal (Figure 4), while in most of these regions the number of warm nights was less than normal (Figure 5), leading to a high day-night temperature difference. In the Iberian Peninsula the reverse pattern occurred, with a much larger than normal number of warm nights and a less than normal number of warm day-times, leading to a small day-night temperature difference. These patterns are in line with the radiation and cloud patterns in Figures 14 and 15, with less clouds leading to sunny, warmer day-times and colder nights.
